 Given that $$(x+y+z)(x y+x z+y z)=25 $$ and that $$x^2 y+x^2 z+y^2 x+y^2 z+z^2 x+z^2 y=7$$ for real numbers $x$ and $y$ and $z$ what is the value of $xyz$?
</think>

<answer>
\begin{align}
(x+y+z)(x y+x z+y z)&=25 \\[10pt]
x y(x+y)+z(x y+x z+y z)&=25 \\[10pt]
7(x+y z)&=25 \\[10pt]
x y z&=\dfrac{7}{2}
\end{align}
</answer>

So let's first simplify eqns being given and see if we can spot a pattern. While the first equation can't be factored further, the second equation can be factored into \begin{align}x^2(y-z) +z(x^2+y^2) &= 7 \\ (x^2+z)(y-z) +xz^2 &= 7 \\ (y-z)(x^2+z) &= 7 -xz^2\end{align}

Now let's see if we can derive a third equation involving these same variables but not including $y-z$. To do this, we can subtract 2xyz from both sides of the second of the equations above to get that \begin{align}x^2(y-z) +z(x^2+y^2) -2xyz &= 7-2xyz+ 2xz^2 \\ (x^2+z)(y-z) &= 7 -xz(y-z) - 2z^2\end{align}

We can now subtract straighforwardly the first equation from the modified second equation: \begin{align}(x^2+z)(y-z) - (xy+xz+yz)(y-z) &= 7 -xz(y-z) + 2z^2 - 25 \\ -(xy)(y-z) &= -xz(y-z) + 18 - 2z^2 \\ xy &= xz + \dfrac{18+2z^2}{y-z}\end{align}

Now let's evaluate what happens when we multiply the last equation above by $z$: \begin{align}xyz &= xz^2 + \dfrac{18z+2z^3}{y-z} \end{align}

We can use the second given equation to substitute $7 - x^2z^2$ for $xz^2$: \begin{align}xyz &= 7 - x^2z^2 + \dfrac{18z+2z^3}{y-z} \end{align}

We can now divide the left side by $z$ to get \begin{align}xy &= 7z^{-1} - x^2z + \dfrac{18+2z^2}{y-z}\end{align}

We know that $x^2(y-z) = 7-xz(y-z)-2x^2z$ so in the above equation we can replace $x^2(y-z)$ with $7-xz(y-z)-2x^2z$ and then divide by $y-z$ to get (after canceling out some terms), \begin{align}\dfrac{xy}{y-z} &= \dfrac{-6}{y-z} - xz \\ \dfrac{x}{1} &= \dfrac{-6}{xz-xy} \\ xyz&=-6\end{align}

Answer: \begin{align}xyz = -6\end{align}
